WD STD Analysis

Chao-Sheng, Wu

Goal

Which items influence WD STD most ?
How do these items influence WD STD ?

How to manipulate the hardwares such that we can lower WD STD ?

Say Hello to our Data

Load our data, and have a look !

data <- read.csv("PDS_Join_ItemPL.csv") 
data <- as_tibble(data) 
data_backup <- as_tibble(data)
datatable(data[1:100,c(1:200,1500:1755)] ,
          fillContainer = T ,
          height = 600, options = list(scrollY = 350))

The structure of our columns : \[ \begin{matrix} \text{LOT_ID} & \text{WFR_ID} & \{ \; Layer_lItem_i \; \mid for \; 1 \leq l \leq L \; , \; 1 \leq i \leq I_l \; \} & \text{Position_dummy} & \text{X.PL.WD.STD} & \text{X.PL.WD.AVG} \end{matrix} \]

We can expand the predictors : \[ \begin{matrix} Layer_1Item_1 & Layer_1Item_2 & Layer1Item_3 & \cdots & Layer1Item_{I_1} \\ Layer_2Item_1 & Layer_2Item_2 & Layer2Item_3 & \cdots & Layer1Item_{I_2} \\ Layer_3Item_1 & Layer_3Item_2 & Layer3Item_3 & \cdots & Layer1Item_{I_3} \\ \vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots \\ Layer_LItem_1 & Layer_LItem_2 & LayerLItem_3 & \cdots & Layer1Item_{I_L} \end{matrix} \] Note : The above matrix

Preprocess

Delete variables which did not involve into reactor chamber

# find all layer names
item_name <- names(data) ; 
layer_name_need_pro <- grep("RealTemp_Outer_WaferTemp", item_name, value = TRUE ) 
layer_name <- sub("RealTemp_Outer_WaferTemp.*$", "", layer_name_need_pro )
length_ln <- length(layer_name) 
# save the names of closed valves
num_cv <- 1
valve_closed <- list() 
for ( i in 1:length_ln ) { 
  
 
  ###########################################################################
  #                                  Bubbler                                #
  ###########################################################################
  
  ## should replace . by \\. in layer_name, but the result is identical ( e.g. DV.Q3.well ) 
  pattern_find_Bypass <- paste( "^" , layer_name[i] , "Bubbler_._Bypass.*" , sep = "" )
  
  item_name_Bypass <- grep( pattern_find_Bypass , item_name , value = TRUE )
  
  length_item_Bypass <- length( item_name_Bypass )
   
  
  ## Note : since 3_Bypass was not recorded, just delete them to simpify analysis
  
  ## Delete Bubbler03 items 
  pattern_delete_Bubbler03 <- paste( layer_name[i] , "Bubbler03" , sep = "" ) 
  ## item with words : Bubbler03 
  item_delete_Bubbler03 <- grep( pattern_delete_Bubbler03 , item_name , value = TRUE )  
  data[ , item_delete_Bubbler03 ] <- NULL 
  
  
  ## find number after Bubbler >> want { 1 2 4 5 6 8 9 } : the numbers are assuming unknown 
  ## also the corresponding mean of the *_Bypass respectivly 
  ## and delete Bubbler0* items with *_Bypass mean > 2 
  for ( j in 1:length_item_Bypass ) { 
    Bypass_j <- item_name_Bypass[j] 
    
    number_Bypass_j <- Bypass_j %>%  
                          str_extract("_[0-9]_") %>%  
                          str_extract("[0-9]") 
    
    values_Bypass <- data[ , Bypass_j ]
    value <- mean(values_Bypass[[1]]) 
    
    if ( value > 2 ){
       
      ## find items with Bubbler0j and delete all 
      pattern_delete_Bubbler0j <- paste( layer_name[i] , "Bubbler0" , number_Bypass_j , ".*" , sep = "" )
      item_delete_Bubbler0j <- grep( pattern_delete_Bubbler0j , item_name , value = TRUE ) 
      
      data[ , item_delete_Bubbler0j ] <- NULL 
      
      data[ , Bypass_j ] <- NULL  ## valve's value should not influence WD STD
      
      ##### save name of closed valves 
      valve_closed[[num_cv]] <- Bypass_j
      num_cv <- num_cv + 1;
    }
    else {
      data[ , Bypass_j ] <- NULL  
    }
  
  }
  
  
  ###########################################################################   
  ###########################################################################
  ###########################################################################   
  ###########################################################################
  #                                  SiH403                                 #
  ###########################################################################
  
  pattern_find_Gas <- paste( layer_name[i] , "Gas_3" , sep = "") 
  item_Gas <- grep( pattern_find_Gas , item_name , value = TRUE )
  values_Valve_SiH403 <-  data[ , item_Gas ]
  value_Valve_SiH403 <- mean(values_Valve_SiH403[[1]])
  
  if ( value_Valve_SiH403 < 1 ){
    pattern_delete_SiH403 <- paste( layer_name[i] , "SiH403" , sep = "" )
    item_delete_SiH403 <- grep( pattern_delete_SiH403 , item_name , value = TRUE )
    data[ , item_delete_SiH403 ] <- NULL
    data[ , item_Gas ] <- NULL
    
    #### save name of closed valve
    valve_closed[[num_cv]] <- item_Gas
    num_cv <- num_cv + 1;
  }
  
  else{
    data[ , item_Gas ] <- NULL
    
    ####### combime MFC, DDMFC, PushMFC
    ## find the three columns for each layer
    pattern_MFC <- paste("^" , layer_name[i] , "SiH403_MFC.*" , sep="") ;
    pattern_Push <- paste("^" , layer_name[i] , "SiH403_PushMFC.*" , sep="") ;
    pattern_DD <- paste("^" , layer_name[i] , "SiH403_DDMFC.*" , sep="") ;
    
    item_name_MFC <- grep( pattern_MFC , item_name , value=TRUE ) ;
    item_name_Push <- grep( pattern_Push , item_name , value=TRUE ) ;
    item_name_DD <- grep( pattern_DD , item_name , value=TRUE ) ;
    
    Si_MFC <- data[,item_name_MFC] ;
    Si_Push <- data[,item_name_Push] ;
    Si_DD <- data[,item_name_DD] ;
    
    Si_Mixed <- ( Si_MFC*Si_DD ) / ( Si_MFC + Si_Push ) ; 
    ## Add column
    column_name_add <- paste( layer_name[i] , 'SiH403_Mixed' , sep="") ;
    data[column_name_add] <- Si_Mixed ;
    #add_column(data, column_name_add = Si_Mixed, .before = Position_dummy)
    ## Delete the three columns
    data[ , c( item_name_MFC , item_name_Push , item_name_DD ) ] <- NULL ;
    
  }
  
  
}

Pseudo-replication

To average the replications is a reasonable way.

movetolast <- function(data, move) {
  data[c(setdiff(names(data), move), move)]
}
## the data is refer to the data after "Abnormal Data Checking.R"
data_need_avg_pre <- data ;
#may do some preprocess
data_need_avg <- data_need_avg_pre ; 
all_levels <- levels(data_need_avg$LOT_ID) ;
length_levels <- length(all_levels) ;   
Results_hm <- data.frame() ;
data_avg <- data_need_avg %>%
                  select( -"WFR_ID",-"Position_dummy",-"X.PL.WD.AVG" )  %>% 
                  movetolast("X.PL.WD.STD") %>%   
                  group_by(LOT_ID) %>% 
                  summarize_all( mean , na.rm=TRUE ) 
[1]  58 605

Data Normalization

data_normalization_hm <- data_avg  %>% 
                          select(-"LOT_ID" , -"X.PL.WD.STD")  %>% 
                          scale(center = FALSE , scale = FALSE) 
data_normalization_hm <- cbind.data.frame( data_avg[,"LOT_ID"] , 
                                           data_normalization_hm , 
                                           data_avg[,"X.PL.WD.STD"] )

Multicollinearity Test

Correlation for each layer

for ( i in 1:length(layer_name) ) {
  ## need to avoiding find ?W in W pattern
  A <- grep(layer_name[i] , names(data_normalization_hm) ,  value=TRUE)
  B <- grep( paste(layer_name[i],"W",sep="") , names(data_normalization_hm) ,  value=TRUE)
  temp_name <- setdiff(A,B)
  
  cor_layer <- cor(data_normalization_hm[,c(temp_name,"X.PL.WD.STD")], 
                   use="pairwise.complete.obs")
  
  cor_sorted <- as.matrix(sort(cor_layer[,'X.PL.WD.STD'], decreasing = TRUE))
  #select only high corelations
  CorHigh <- names(which(apply(cor_sorted, 1, function(x) abs(x)>0.1)))
  cor_layer <- cor_layer[CorHigh, CorHigh]
  
  
  corrplot.mixed(cor_layer, 
                 tl.col="black", 
                 tl.pos = "lt" , 
                 tl.cex = 0.63
                 )
  
  
}
rm(temp_name,cor_layer,cor_sorted,CorHigh,A,B)

Take off one of the two items with correlation = 1

for ( i in 1:length(layer_name) ){

  temp_name <- paste( layer_name[i] , "Bubbler09_BathTemp.VALUE" , sep= "")
  
  temp_name2 <- paste( layer_name[i] , "Bubbler01_BathTemp.VALUE" , sep= "")
  
  data_normalization_hm[,temp_name] <- NULL
  
  data_normalization_hm[,temp_name2] <- NULL
  
 
}
rm(temp_name)

Test more formally

for ( i in 22:24 ){
  A <- grep(layer_name[i] , names(data_normalization_hm) ,  value=TRUE)
  B <- grep( paste(layer_name[i],"W",sep="") , names(data_normalization_hm) ,  value=TRUE)
  temp_name <- setdiff(A,B)
  
  temp_data <- data_normalization_hm[,c(temp_name,"X.PL.WD.STD")]
  
  
  model <- lm(X.PL.WD.STD ~. , data=temp_data)
  print(colldiag(model))
}
rm(A,B,temp_name,temp_data,model)

  • DV.Q2.Barrier2 : Bubbler01_DDMFC , Bubbler02_MFC

  • DV.Q2.Barrier3 : Bubbler02_MFC , Bubbler09_MFC , Center_Purge_N2_MFC_49

  • DV.Q2.pre.cap : Bubbler02_MFC , Bubbler08_PressureControllerPC90

Generally speaking, take out 1 item of each multicollinear relationship.

Its Time to Model !!!

Seperate our data into training and test set

library(ISLR) ;
library(glmnet) ;
library(dplyr) ;
library(tidyr) ;
row.names(data_normalization_hm) <- data_normalization_hm$LOT_ID
data_normalization_hm[,"LOT_ID"] <- NULL
X <- model.matrix(X.PL.WD.STD ~ ., data = data_normalization_hm)[,-1] 
y <- data_normalization_hm$X.PL.WD.STD ;
set.seed(2) ;
train =  data_normalization_hm %>%
  sample_frac(0.6) ;
test = data_normalization_hm %>%
  setdiff(train) ;
x_train = model.matrix(X.PL.WD.STD~., train)[,-1]
x_test = model.matrix(X.PL.WD.STD~., test)[,-1]
y_train = train %>% 
  select(X.PL.WD.STD)  %>% 
  unlist() %>% 
  as.numeric() 
y_test = test %>%
  select(X.PL.WD.STD)  %>%
  unlist() %>%
  as.numeric()

Limitations of Lasso 1. In the p>n case, lasso selects at most n variables. 2. If there is a group of variables among which the pairwise correlations
are very high, then the lasso tends to select only one variable from the
group and does not care which one is selected.
